  "prompt": "How do I know who is following me on Snapchat?",
  "response": "Snapchat doesn't have a traditional \"followers\" system like Instagram or Twitter. Instead, you have friends. Here's how you see who's added you and are effectively \"following\" your public stories:\n\n*   **Check Your \"Added Me\" List:** This is the closest thing Snapchat has to a follower list.\n    1.  Open Snapchat.\n    2.  Tap your profile icon (your Bitmoji or profile picture) in the top left corner.\n    3.  Look for the \"Add Friends\" section.\n    4.  Tap on \"Added Me.\" This will show you a list of people who have added you as a friend.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Mutual Following (Friends):** On Snapchat, you typically both have to add each other to be considered friends. So, seeing someone on your \"Added Me\" list and then adding them back makes them your friend.\n*   **Public Profile vs. Private Account:**\n    *   **Private Account:** If your account is private, only people you've added back can see your stories and send you snaps.\n    *   **Public Profile:** If you have a public profile, anyone can subscribe to your public story without you adding them back as a friend.\n*   **Subscribers:** If you have a public profile, you can view the number of subscribers on your public story by viewing the insights of your public story. However, you cannot see the usernames of each subscriber.\n\n**In Summary:**\n\nWhile Snapchat doesn't explicitly label \"followers,\" checking your \"Added Me\" list and setting up a public profile can give you insight into who is following you. However, it's designed more for close connections than broadcasting to a vast audience like other social media platforms.",
